On 21 March the Government of Ghana announced the closure of the country’s borders, including the suspension of international flights and the closure of all land borders until further notice. There are currently no commercial options available to leave Ghana.
UK Special Flights
On 23 May the UK will operate a special flight from Ghana to the UK. This flight is for British visitors to Ghana who have registered to return to the UK but were not accommodated on previous repatriation flights. The registration for these flights is now closed.
Only those who registered for the previous UK special flight will be contacted and invited to book a seat.
Sign up for travel advice email alerts and follow the British High Commission on Twitter and Facebook.
Tickets will not be on sale at the airport. Do not travel to the airport without a confirmed ticket.
You may find it helpful to read our guide to eligibility and the booking process for special charter flights.
Travel to Accra airport
The government of Ghana has lifted its restriction of movement in Greater Accra and Greater Kumasi effective from 1am GMT Monday 20 April. Domestic flights are permitted to fly - contact your local airline for details
If you’re currently outside Accra and seeking to return to the UK, you should travel to Accra as soon as possible
Your journey home
The National Travel Health Network and Centre (NaTHNaC) provides advice on how to stay safe as you travel by air.
When you arrive back in the UK, follow the guidance for when you return to the UK on steps you should take to protect yourself and others.
Future options
The UK government is working closely with airlines and other governments to ensure commercial options for returning to the UK are available as soon as possible.
Sign up for travel advice email alerts and follow the British High Commission on Twitter and Facebook.
If you cannot leave Ghana
If you cannot leave Ghana at this time, see advice on staying in Ghana during coronavirus.
See more information and advice about staying where you are if you cannot return to the UK.
Help and support
If you need urgent consular assistance, you can contact the British High Commission on +233 302 213 250. We are currently experiencing a high volume of calls and as a result our response may be slower than usual.
The High commission cannot provide further information or advice about departure options over the phone. This page will be updated when departure options become available. To get the latest information, sign up for the travel advice email alerts.
Further information
See additional advice on making travel plans to return to the UK, or what to do if you cannot travel immediately.
